\par <I> <h> }{\fs24 <#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 Dairying}{\fs24\lang2057  </h>
\par <h> }{\fs24 <#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 The importance of a crush}{\fs24\lang2057  </h>
\par }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 For assured efficiency in production, a numbe
r of farm buildings or structures are necessary to the dairy enterprise - the milking shed, calf pen, feed store fences. <#/>But there is one structure that some farmers have not put up - the crush.
\par <#/>A crush is any contrived structure meant for the restraining of an animal's movement for easy handling whenever such a need arises.
\par <#/>Most farms have crushes. <#/>One would take it that all farmers have a crush because hardly does one come across a farm without. <#/>So when one farm proves an exception to this rule, then we expect that the farmer has some problem.
\par <#/>As to the necessity for a crush, here is a certain farmer's experience to support this need.
\par <#/>The farmer had come to report that his calf was sick.
\par <#/>Having confirmed from two chief symptoms - difficult breathing and abnormally enlarged superficial lymph glands - that the calf was suffering from East Coast Fever, I asked him to put the calf in a crush so that I could give the animal an injection.

\par <#/>He looked at me curiously and asked wha
t I meant by "crush". <#/>When I had explained the meaning of the word, he threw his head back and laughed. <#/>A crush? <#/>what for? <#/>I will hold this calf with my bare hands and it won't move! <#/>I was a wrestler in my youth, you know."
\par <#/>He cooed
 to the calf and held it firmly. <#/>But what he had not anticipated happened. <#/>The injection needle proved strong and the calf jumped <-/wildy>, falling on top of the stunned old man. <#/>The calf narrowly missed stepping on his stomach. <#/>I was the
refore not astonished when the old man stood up and asked "How does one construct a crush? <#/>"
\par In another instance, a farmer called me to treat her cow whose one teat was producing bloody milk, an <-/abvious> symptom of mastitis. <#/>This farmer, like the
 other one, had no crush but she said that her animal was quite gentle and that she milked it without first tying it.
\par <#/>True to the farmer's word, the cow did not resist being injected. <#/>But only the owner could touch its udder without any fuss. <#/>So she emptied the antibiotic infusion into the teat.
\par <#/>Other than for the purpose of restraining animals to give them treatment, a crush can be put into many other uses.
\par <#/>For small-scale farmers with one or two milk animals, the crush can be roofed to double up as a milking shed instead of tying the animal to a tree when milking.
\par <#/>When de-worming or drenching to control internal parasites - worms - handling <-/f> adult cattle calls for a crush.
\par <#/>If the farmer is to use Artificial Insemination (AI) instead of a bull, then he will need a crush.
\par <X_>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Some farm operations, such as de-worming, ear-tagging, ear-notching, or branding, require that the animal be well-restrained. So much valuable time is wasted trying to chase an animal throughout the farm to g
ive an identification mark, for instance. Such chases lead to animals being injured as they try to jump over fences to get away.
\par For the purpose of disease <-/con-control>, a crush provides a good place to do supplementary measures of tick control after animals have been dipped.
\par Hand-dressing animals with tick chemicals (of the greasy nature) applied on favourite tick attachment sites and hand removal of ticks from the animals' body are thus made possible.
\par If a farmer wishes to practise hand-spraying, then a crush becomes a necessary structure. More significantly, pregnant or sick animals which cannot be dipped can be <-/convenietly> hand-sprayed at home in such a structure.
\par When planning for a crush, site is an important consideration. The farmer should cho
ose a level site on the part of the farm that he knows that he won't employ in any other form of agricultural production. <-/Preferrably>, this should be some distance from the farmer's houses.
\par The length of the crush will depend on the maximum number of a
nimals that will need to be handled at one go. However, this does not mean that if a farmer has 10 animals then, he builds a crush long enough for these animals to stand one behind the other at a reasonable distance. Rather, the idea is to pack the animal
s in such a way that they are comfortable but also fully restrained.
\par Constructing a crush is a simple affair and does not require the opinion of a qualified architecture. No complex design or elaborate sketch is needed.
\par As long as the structure constructed is capable of holding animals without any problem, then that is enough. An excessively expensive crush is an <-/unecessary> waste of farm income.
\par To reduce the cost of construction, the farmer should choose inexpensive material. If alternative materials are available and relatively cheaper, <-_the> they should be preferred.
\par Several standing posts or poles, four side rails, four sliding bars - all wooden materials - and nails are the materials required. The sliding bars are for closing the crush on either entrance once the animals are inside. }{\fs24\lang2057 </X>
