\par }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 The importance of the agro-chemical industry in Kenya lies in the fact that agriculture is economy's mainstay. <#/>With over
 80 per cent of Kenya's land being low and medium potential, agricultural activities are mainly concentrated on the remaining 20 per cent of the land. <#/>At the same time over 80 per cent of the population directly depends on agriculture for subsistence.

\par <#/>It is projected that there will be 35 million people in the country by the year 2000. <#/>It is, therefore, the Government's policy to expand food production to cater for the fast increasing population.
\par <#/>The Ministry of Agriculture has formulated a number of strategies to increase yields per hectare and reduce crop losses.
\par <#/>Meeting the growing demand for food is a great challenge to Kenyans as our farmers work to increase food supply. <#/>To expand agricultural production and increase exports the 
farmers must use the best seeds, fertilisers and crop protection facilities available today.
\par <#/>Pesticides are very important in this process because, about 20 per cent of Kenyan crop is lost either in the field or in the store due to pest damage.
\par <#/>Tak
e cotton or coffee, for example. <#/>A farmer must maintain regular sprays to control pest damage. <#/>If this is not done, yields will be affected, farmers are aware of this and what they need to know most are what pesticides can be used and when to use 
them in order to maximise results - and improve yields - the same with livestock.
\par <#/>The use of pesticides has become an important feature and efforts have been made towards educating farmers on the effective use of the same under the current three years' 
"Kenya safe use project" sponsored by the Brussel based International Group of Nations Associations of Agro-chemical Manufacturers (GIFAP).
\par <#/>In recognition of the importance of pesticides to the economy, an increasing amount of the resources has been al
located for the importation of pesticides. <#/>The country spends Sh700 million on such imports the bulk of which are used locally for pest and disease control, with about 5 per cent being <-_re-export><+_re-exported> to the neighbouring countries in the 
spirit of regional co-operation in pest and disease control.
\par <#/>Pesticides have played an important role in the improvement of human welfare all over the world. <#/>This is equally true in Kenya where agriculture is mainstay of the economy. <#/>The questio
n as to why we need pesticides in this country was put to Mr Clive Mutiso, the chairman of Pesticide Chemicals Association of Kenya (PCAK) in an interview with this writer.
\par <#/>Mr Mutiso observed that crop protection products must be biologically active to
 do their job properly and so they do carry an element of risk but a great deal of time and money, he added, is invested in research and listing the highest possible safety standards to man and the environment.
\par <#/>He commended PCAK for the key role it is 
playing in the development of agrochemical industry in the country. <#/>About 20 per cent of all pesticides used in the country are formulated locally while the balance is imported already formulated. <#/>With regard to regulation and better management of
 this industry the Pest Control Products Act of 1982 has a long way in facilitating the consolidation of the industry. <#/>A number of Government organisations closely monitor the formulation and quality of agrochemicals in the country.
\par <#/>With the help of
 PCAK the National Agricultural Laboratories (NAL) and Pest Control Products Board (PCPB) usually receive and analyse samples of the products formulated. <#/>Currently the pesticides industry itself is the most potent force for the safe and correct use of
 the products and this is perhaps more evident in a developing country such as Kenya than elsewhere. <#/>The majority of pesticides imported in the country originate from the major companies in Europe and the United States.
\par <#/>The Government has enacted ef
fective legislation to regulate the pesticides industry at all levels. <#/>The implementation of the act according to Mr Bob Combes "Kenya safe use project" leader, is still proceeding with the industry endeavouring to co-operate with the Government to fo
rmulate practical solution to various problems.
\par <X_>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Mr Combes notes that there are approximately 100 sales and technical representatives of chemical companies operating in Kenya. Most of these, he said, have frequent contact with distributors and traders at all
 levels and their role in educating the two is extremely important.
\par He said "safe use project" which has funded 14 research-based multi-national chemical companies, with the help of the <-/Brussel>-based GIFAP, constitutes the most effective force in promo
ting the correct use of pesticides through the on-going training programmes which are targeted at the trader and extension officers who are in direct contact with farmers.
\par Mr Combes said the three year "safe use project" current
ly with the help of major agrochemical companies in Kenya are already in the field on demonstration to small-scale farmers throughout the country on the correct application methods and safety standards in the use of the pesticides.
\par With the "safe use project" exercise going on, a number of farmers in the countryside are directly exposed to the training programmes and is the most effective way of promoting proper pesticide use.
\par Before reaching the farmers, GIFAP and Kenya's based PCAK initiated the agro-chemical companies representatives in the country to train operators in the field under the system of "Train the trainers".
\par Apart from these training programmes, the project has access to safety posters which are very useful as a constant reminder of the hazards inherent in pesticide use and they are in illustrated in graph form }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>grammar}{
\v\fs24\lang2057  so that the message is comprehensive to all the users.
\par Government legislation requires that information given on the pesticide labels have to be comprehensive since this is the only instruction, display, warning or communication which reaches every user.
\par The project is emphasising protective clothing. For example, plantation workers are supposed to be supplied with boots, capes, overalls, hats and gloves and in some cases fac
e masks. The project is recommending good protection against pesticide spray, comfortable to wear though reasonably hardy, washable and cheap clothing.
\par While emphasis has been put on the benefits derived from the use of pesticides, caution must be exercise
d not to misuse pesticides as this can endanger the health of the users and the general public as well as polluting the environment. Although many people today have great fear of the use of pesticides, the "safe use project" would like to allay those fear
s and encourage greater understanding and knowledge concerning the true benefits which pesticides provide.
\par The "safe use project" training officer, Mr Edward Njer, claimed that for the benefit of mankind, pesticides continue to play vital roles in combating
 famine, diseases and epidemics. He said the population of the world would certainly be worse off if pesticides were no longer applied in the farming industry.
\par With the major development created by man, there is always a consequential series of risks and effects, he said adding "even the development of the internal combustion engine and the motor car has its side effects".
\par Mr Njer claimed pollution from exhaust emission, death and destruction on the roads are everyday <-/occurances> but we see no major dema
nds to stop using motor transport, only pressure for the need to introduce controls to prevent the abuse of a very valuable implement in terms of mankind's development.
\par While Mr Combes notes that panic, scaremongering headlines in both local and internatio
nal press concerning pesticides, do nothing to help solve the problems which exist at the consumer level. He said it is up to the project agrochemical industries, PCAK, PCPB and the government to ensure that the abuse of pesticides is reduced to insignifi
cant levels.
\par Professor D.N. Mukunya points out in his papers "Sustaining a green revolution in eastern Africa" that it is an indisputable fact the pesticides have played an important role in increasing food production and meeting public health.
\par He notes that farmers must continue to be educated on the safe and effective use of pesticides so that this region can continue to expand agricultural production while protecting our valuable natural resources.
\par The paper notes further that pesticides have also played a major role in reclaiming formerly uninhabitable environments infested with disease-carrying insects. }{\fs24\lang2057 </X>
