\par }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 "All that glitters is not gold" is a familiar proverb whose truism can as well stand for the fact that glitter is not the only determinant that a gem is "gold" (the sparkle may be hidden or obscured by
 a thick dust coat!). <#/>Simply, the ordinariness, <-/lacklusture> or commonplace quality of some things masks or keeps under the surface the object's grand qualities.
\par <#/>For quite some time I had been on the look-out for any farmer using a structure that fits the above description in relation to other types of structures serving the same purpose of milk-cooling.
\par <#/>About two months ago, a friend told me of a farm with such a structure. <#/>Quite ordinary looking, resembling a small cupboard and rare in 
many farms and homes, this is a gadget whose owners have come to like as an invaluable home appliance. <#/>The owner of the farm I visited speaks well of the device.
\par <#/>He revealed to me that were it not for that charcoal-cooler, he would not have <-/benefitted> much from dairying.
\par <#/>A year ago there was no milk collection centre near his home. <#/>Many farmers in the area were forced to sell milk to the neighbours. <#/>But the farmers found it a big problem keeping evening milk in good condition to be sold in the morning.
\par <#/>Salvation came to that farmer when he saw a <ea/>Jua <ea/>Kali cooler in another farm and observed how it worked. <#/>He decided that he too should have one. <#/>Until the material he used rusted and started giving food an abnormal 
smell, the farmer has been using the cooler not only for milk but also for preserving other food\-stuffs. <#/>However, he does not miss the cooler's services as he would have a year ago since now a milk-collection centre has been opened up in his area.

\par <#/>
Milk cooling using whatever type of a cooler is one of the most important operations in the dairy industry. <#/>Cooled milk stays for long at high quality levels. <#/>This helps to check the enormous losses that would occur in the overall production proce
ss since milk spoilage is greatly reduced.
\par <#/>Usually milk that has turned sour or has been heavily contaminated with bacteria and other foreign objects by the time of arrival at its place of disposal will be rejected.
\par <#/>Milk must be suitably cooled if the time taken to transport it to its destination is long.
\par <#/>By cooling one aims at stopping bacterial activities as these affect the smell and taste of milk.
\par <#/>Because the bacteria found in milk multiply rapidly in raw milk, it is important that temperature after milking is lowered as soon as possible to keep the bacteria dormant.
\par <#/>Where it is not possible to employ the very expensive open or closed mechanical coolers, one can turn to the cheaper charcoal coolers.
\par <#/>The charcoal-cooler is a very si
mple structure. <#/>It is built to look like a cupboard except that it has a layer of charcoal placed between the outside wall and (mostly but not always) a wire mesh. <#/>The size of the cooler will depend on individual requirements as does compartmental
isation of the cabinet.
\par <#/>Used properly, a charcoal-cooler is capable of cooling milk for two or three days. <#/>Most kitchen foodstuffs can be preserved in this cooler for up to four days.
\par <#/>Operating it is a simple affair. <#/>All that is needed once the structure has been bought is water for effecting the cooling.
\par <#/>The procedure is to pour water on the charcoal in the morning. <#/>To encourage greater cooling or even to ensure cooling while one is not there for many hours, the idea is to put a piec
e of cloth, sack or rag on the top face of the cooler and then to pour water on that material. <#/>Water then drips slowly and evenly on to the charcoal to give sustained and uniform cooling. <#/>The piece of rag should hang evenly on all walls of the str
ucture from the top.
\par <#/>It is unfortunate that few people know of the existence and usefulness of this simple and cheap facility. <#/>However, it is possible to obtain it from the many village polytechnics in the country.
\par <#/>There are people who have adopted this cooler's working mechanism to build "cold rooms".
